From: vyos-ls1046a-build M3-3 step 5 v3 <noreply@vyos-ls1046a-build>
Date: 2026-05-28
Subject: [PATCH] dpaa: TX ZC submission, xsk_tx_inflight backpressure, TxConf round-trip closure (v3: stand-alone)

M3-3 step 5 (spec sec 6.1.4, "TX ZC + backpressure + round-trip closure").
Closes the AF_XDP zero-copy datapath by wiring three new flavor ops into
dpaa_eth_poll() and dpaa_tx_conf():

  1. ops->napi_tx_zc(priv) -- drains XSK Tx ring into DPAA1 egress FQs
     via xsk_tx_peek_release_desc_batch() + qman_enqueue(), honouring
     the software xsk_tx_inflight budget (DPAA1_XSK_TX_MAX_INFLIGHT =
     1024). Called from dpaa_eth_poll() tail inside the same RCU
     read-section as napi_refill (0084) and xsk_set_rx_need_wakeup
     (0080), AFTER napi_complete_done() and BEFORE the QMan DQRR
     interrupt is re-armed. Budget per qband per poll =
     min(MAX_INFLIGHT - inflight, 64).

  2. ops->xsk_set_tx_need_wakeup(priv, np) -- arms XSK tx-need-wakeup
     on every bound qband whose pool requested XDP_USE_NEED_WAKEUP at
     bind time. Userspace observes via xsk_ring_prod__needs_wakeup()
     and issues sendto(MSG_DONTWAIT) which lands in
     af_xdp_pool_xsk_wakeup() and schedules NAPI. Currently set
     unconditionally; future refinement may clear when inflight falls
     below DPAA1_XSK_TX_LOW_WATER (512).

  3. ops->tx_conf_zc(priv, fd) -- TxConf round-trip closure. Called
     from the head of dpaa_tx_conf() BEFORE the skb cleanup path.
     XSK FDs are identified by fd->bpid matching priv->xsk_bpid[q]
     for any bound qband -- the bpid is the claim marker set by
     napi_tx_zc when building the FD. XSK FDs carry NO FM_FD_CMD_FCO
     (the UMEM chunk MUST NOT be released to BMan) and NO skb
     backing. Per claimed FD:
       - atomic_dec(xsk_tx_inflight[q]) frees a budget slot
       - xsk_tx_completed(pool, 1) advances userspace CQ head
       - priv->xsk_tx_conf_zc++ for observability
     Returns true to short-circuit dpaa_cleanup_tx_fd(). With no
     flavor module loaded (default flavor) ops is NULL and the fast
     path falls through to the existing skb cleanup verbatim.

Two new u64 counters on struct dpaa_priv exposed via ethtool -S:

  - xsk_tx_zc_submit -- bumped once per non-empty napi_tx_zc batch.
    Counts BATCHES (not FDs); per-FD counting would dominate the
    cache. Pairs with xsk_tx_backpressure (0079) for spec sec 6.1.4
    "Strict Tx backpressure" observability.

  - xsk_tx_conf_zc -- bumped once per claimed FD in the tx_conf_zc
    hook. xsk_tx_zc_submit - xsk_tx_conf_zc >= 0 always; if the
    difference grows unboundedly the TxConf path is broken
    (FDs not coming back). Under steady state the two counters
    track within (DPAA1_XSK_TX_MAX_INFLIGHT * num_bound_qbands).

The xsk_bpid claim-marker scheme is intentional: it requires zero new
per-FD storage, survives FD demux across CPUs (TxConf may run on a
different CPU than submit), and degrades gracefully on pool detach
(if priv->xsk_bpool[q] becomes NULL between submit and confirm, the
claim still fires on bpid match but the xsk_tx_completed() call is
skipped because pool is NULL -- inflight still atomic_dec's, so the
counter does not drift). The 1024/512 thresholds are tuned for the
LS1046A QMan SWP egress depth (typ. ~256 entries per SWP, 4 SWPs
fan-out, ~1024 max in-flight without bunching).

Strictly NAPI-context on submit; RCU read-section on TxConf. No new
locks: xsk_tx_inflight[] is atomic_t (added in 0070 alongside
xsk_bpid[]) to be lockless against the cross-CPU TxConf path.

THREE INVARIANTS THAT MAKE THE bpid CLAIM SAFE:

  (a) priv->xsk_bpid[q] uniqueness WITHIN a netdev. Each bound qband
      on the same netdev MUST hold a distinct bpid (allocated by the
      flavor module's xsk_pool_attach -- see patch 0075b). Without
      this, two qbands' TxConf streams would alias on bpid match and
      the wrong qband would receive the atomic_dec. The flavor
      module's BMan pool allocator (bman_new_pool()) enforces
      bpid uniqueness across the system -- two concurrently-bound
      XSK pools on the same netdev cannot share a bpid.

  (b) priv->xsk_bpid[q] disambiguation ACROSS netdevs. Two DPAA1
      netdevs (e.g. eth3 and eth4 both running AF_XDP) can hold
      bpids from disjoint subsets of the global BMan bpid space.
      TxConf FDs are dequeued from each netdev's own TxConf FQs
      (priv->egress_fqs[]) -- the FQ-ID demux is the FIRST level of
      separation, and bpid match is checked only against THIS
      netdev's xsk_bpid[] array. So even if two netdevs happen to
      reuse the same bpid value (impossible under bman_new_pool()
      but worth being explicit about), the tx_conf_zc hook would
      never see another netdev's FD.

  (c) priv->xsk_bpid[q] vs the skb-path BMan pool bpid. The
      mainline RX path's dpaa_bp (priv->dpaa_bp) holds its own
      bpid for skb-mode RX. Could fd->bpid on a TxConf path EVER
      equal that bpid by coincidence? No: TX FDs only carry a
      bpid in fd->bpid if the caller set it (the skb TX path
      DOES set it -- the bpid of the SG-frame pool used to build
      the FD), so we must NOT match against the skb-pool's bpid.
      The check is structural: only priv->xsk_bpool[q] non-NULL
      qbands are considered, and priv->xsk_bpid[q] is set ONLY by
      af_xdp_pool_xsk_pool_attach() after a successful XSK pool
      allocation. There is no path that would write a non-XSK bpid
      into priv->xsk_bpid[].

PERFORMANCE COSTS, ALL BOUNDED:

  - Per-FD RCU read-lock in dpaa_tx_conf(). The mainline TxConf
    path is already a hot path (~7+ Gbps = ~600 k FD/s on 10 GbE),
    so a per-FD rcu_read_lock() adds ~5 ns of locked-section cost
    (RCU read-side is a per-CPU counter bump on modern arm64).
    This is acceptable for two reasons: (1) tx_conf_zc returns
    early-true on the first qband match, so the RCU section is
    short; (2) batching the rcu_dereference across a TxConf NAPI
    dequeue burst would require restructuring dpaa_tx_conf() to
    accept a batch (not currently the case) -- the per-FD cost is
    the design choice mainline already makes for every other hook
    in this path.

  - O(qbands) bpid scan in tx_conf_zc. Bounded by
    DPAA1_XSK_MAX_QBANDS = 4. At ~600 k FD/s with 4 qbands, that
    is ~2.4 M loop iterations per second -- ~10 ns per FD on
    Cortex-A72, totally negligible relative to the FD's own cost
    (DMA unmap, percpu_priv accounting, network stack handoff).

  - egress_fq selection by raw_smp_processor_id() % dpaa_max_num_txqs().
    Under v2 single-CPU pinning the submit side only runs on
    priv->qmap[q].cpu, so this modulo always produces the same FQ
    index for a given qband. That is exactly the desired property:
    each qband's XSK Tx stream lands on a single TX FQ, so QMan
    SWP scheduling stays single-producer per FQ (no per-FQ
    serialization contention). Documented; do not "improve" this
    to per-qband fixed FQ assignment without measuring -- the
    current expression is equivalent for the pinned submit path
    and works correctly if cross-CPU submit is ever re-introduced.

v2 (2026-05-27) -- option-c single-CPU pinning on the submit side, for
the same reason as 0084v2: xsk_tx_peek_release_desc_batch() advances
the XSK Tx ring's SPSC consumer cursor (uapi/linux/if_xdp.h contract),
so concurrent per-CPU NAPI tails racing on the same qband would
corrupt that cursor identically to how v1 0084 corrupted the fill
ring's producer cursor. Mirror the 0084v2 fix exactly: each qband
has a single owner CPU (priv->qmap[q].cpu, populated by M3-3 step 2a's
per_cpu_ptr() wiring at xsk_pool_attach time). Add an early-return
`if (raw_smp_processor_id() != priv->qmap[q].cpu) continue;` inside
the per-qband loop body of af_xdp_pool_napi_tx_zc() BEFORE the
xsk_tx_peek_release_desc_batch() call.

CRITICAL: tx_conf_zc() is NOT gated by CPU. The whole bpid-claim
scheme is designed for cross-CPU demux -- TxConf FDs come back on
whichever CPU the QMan TxConf FQ is bound to, which is independent
of the submitting CPU. Adding a CPU check to tx_conf_zc() would
silently drop FDs whose matching qband-owner CPU is not the current
CPU, leaking inflight budget and never advancing the userspace CQ
head. xsk_tx_inflight[] is atomic_t precisely to be lockless under
this asymmetry; the xsk_tx_completed(pool, 1) call is XSK-API-
internally serialized.

v3 (2026-05-28) -- stand-alone redesign. The v2 patch was correct
on the wire but the changelog left several invariants implicit:
the bpid-uniqueness rules (a/b/c above), the per-FD RCU cost
justification, the O(qbands) scan bound, and the egress-FQ-vs-pinning
relationship. v3 makes all of these explicit in the kerneldoc so
that future changes to the TxConf path (e.g. M3-3 step 6+ true ZC
RX, which may add more flavor-op hooks to dpaa_tx_conf) do not
accidentally violate them. The DPAA_ENQUEUE_RETRIES = 100000
inline constant is documented as a stable upper bound on QMan EQCR
slot-refill latency -- the value has not changed in dpaa_eth.c
since the driver was upstreamed in 4.16. No code changes vs v2.

